### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core, router

### Is this a regression?

Yes

### Description

I'm unsure on whether to call this a bug, but in case it's not, is there a workaround for this issue I'm getting? 

My company has a multi-tenant product, and all of the urls in our product have an id to identify the customer we have selected. To avoid putting an extra queryParam in every `routerLink`, we created our own `myRouterLink` like this:

```typescript
@Directive({
    selector: "[myRouterLink]",
    standalone: false
})
export class MyRouterLinkDirective extends RouterLink {

    @Input()
    set myRouterLink(commands: any[] | string | null | undefined) {
        super.routerLink = commands;
    }

    get urlTree(): UrlTree {
        const { myCustId } = this.activatedRoute.snapshot.queryParams;

        const urlTree = super.urlTree;
        urlTree.queryParams.myCustId = myCustId;
        return urlTree;
    }
}
```

This had been working fine for several versions of Angular, even in Angular 20. But in Angular 21, [this commit](https://github.com/angular/angular/commit/89d47d814de1e57c0b64ff1167ce9f86c518c670) changed the implementation, even though `urlTree` still exists, it is no longer invoked by `onClick`, instead `onClick` invokes `_urlTree` which is marked as `@internal` so Angular's compiler wouldn't let me override it:

## Before
```typescript
  @HostListener('click', [ ... ])
  onClick( ... ): boolean {
    const urlTree = this.urlTree;
    ....
  }

  get urlTree(): UrlTree | null {
     // ... actual implementation here ...
   }
```

## After
```typescript
  @HostListener('click', [ ... ])
  onClick( ... ): boolean {
    const urlTree = this._urlTree();
    ....
  }

  get urlTree(): UrlTree | null {
    return untracked(this._urlTree);
  }

  /** @internal */
  _urlTree = computed(() => { 
     // ... actual implementation here ...
  })
```

This change means the behaviour we depend on is not longer achievable, or at least in an even uncleaner way.

So, is there a way I can achieve the old effect in a way that is less prone to break in future updates? Or, can the current implementation be changed back in a way the _urlTree method is not internal?

Thanks.

